modules.title: Comprehensive Teacher Training
modules.description: A complete guide for preschool teachers covering philosophy, safety, pedagogy, and daily operations.

pages.title: Welcome kit (vision, values, culture, expectations)
pages.content:
Purpose of This Session

  • Understand who we are as a preschool

  • Align with our purpose and philosophy

  • Clearly know what is expected of them

  • Feel welcomed, confident, and prepared before entering the classroom

This is not just an introduction ‚Äî it is the foundation of professional alignment.

A. Welcome Message to New Teachers

Objective

To create a sense of belonging, respect, and pride in joining the preschool.

Key Elements

  • Warm welcome from management/principal/academic head

  • Acknowledgement of the teacher‚Äôs role as a shaper of young lives

  • Assurance of support, training, and mentorship

  • Emphasis that teachers are partners in the school‚Äôs journey, not just employees

Core Message

‚ÄúYou are not just joining a school. You are joining a place where childhood is respected, learning is joyful, and teachers are trusted guides.‚Äù

B. Preschool Vision

What is Vision?

The vision defines where we want to go and what kind of children we want to nurture.

Vision Orientation for Teachers

  • Education beyond academics

  • Focus on happy, confident, curious children

  • Strong foundation for lifelong learning

  • Safe, respectful, and inclusive environment

Teacher Alignment

  • Teach with purpose, not pressure

  • Prioritize emotional well-being over performance

  • Respect childhood pace and individuality

C. Preschool Mission (How We Achieve the Vision)

Mission Focus Areas

  • Play-based and activity-based learning

  • Child-centric classroom practices

  • Strong parent-teacher partnership

  • Continuous teacher learning and growth

  • Safe, hygienic, and nurturing environment

Teacher‚Äôs Role in the Mission

  • Deliver learning through joy, patience, and creativity

  • Observe, support, and guide ‚Äî not rush or compare

  • Communicate honestly and respectfully with parents

  • Follow systems, routines, and SOPs consistently

D. Core Values of the Preschool

Why Values Matter

Values guide daily decisions, behavior, and interactions inside the school.

Key Values Explained to Teachers

Value

Description

Child First

  • Every decision is taken in the best interest of the child

  • Emotional safety is non-negotiable

  • No shaming, threatening, or fear-based discipline

Respect & Dignity

  • Every child is treated with respect

  • Teachers speak kindly, patiently, and calmly

  • No labeling or comparison of children

Care & Compassion

  • Teachers act with empathy and understanding

  • Children‚Äôs feelings are acknowledged

  • Mistakes are treated as learning opportunities

Professional Integrity

  • Honesty, punctuality, and responsibility

  • Confidentiality of child and parent information

  • Ethical conduct at all times

Teamwork & Collaboration

  • Teachers support each other

  • Open communication with coordinators

  • Respect for all staff members

E. School Culture

What is School Culture?

School culture is ‚Äúhow things are done here‚Äù ‚Äî daily behavior, attitude, and environment.

Culture Highlights

  • Calm, warm, and welcoming classrooms

  • Positive language and gentle guidance

  • Structured routines with flexibility

  • Open communication and mutual respect

Expected Teacher Behavior

  • Smile, greet children and parents warmly

  • Maintain a calm tone even during challenges

  • Model good manners and emotional control

  • Follow routines consistently

F. Professional Expectations from New Teachers

1. Classroom Expectations

  • Be prepared before children arrive

  • Maintain classroom safety and hygiene

  • Engage children actively, not passively

  • Observe children closely and document learning

2. Conduct Expectations

  • Maintain professional boundaries

  • Follow dress code and communication norms

  • Avoid gossip or negative discussions

  • Uphold school reputation inside and outside the campus

3. Learning & Growth Expectations

  • Attend all training sessions

  • Be open to feedback and coaching

  • Ask questions and seek clarification

  • Continuously improve teaching practices

G. Teacher as a Role Model

Teachers are constantly observed and imitated by children.

Teachers Are Expected To Model

  • Respectful speech and behavior

  • Patience and emotional control

  • Honesty and fairness

  • Curiosity and love for learning

‚ÄúChildren may forget what we teach, but they never forget how we made them feel.‚Äù

H. Support System for New Teachers

Support Provided

  • Mentor / senior teacher guidance

  • Structured induction training

  • Regular check-ins during probation

  • Open-door communication with coordinators

Message to New Teachers

You are not expected to know everything on Day One.

Mistakes are part of learning. Support is always available.

I. Induction Acknowledgement & Alignment

At the end of this session, new teachers are expected to:

  • Understand the preschool‚Äôs vision and values

  • Accept professional and ethical expectations

  • Commit to following school culture and practices

(Optional)

  • Signed acknowledgement form

  • Induction checklist completion

pages.title: Appointment documentation, staff file & verification checklist
pages.content:
Purpose of This Module

This module ensures that:

  • All teachers are legally, professionally, and ethically verified.

  • The school meets safety, compliance, and audit requirements.

  • Teachers clearly understand their employment status, responsibilities, and obligations.

PRO-TIP: Documentation is not a formality ‚Äî it is a child safety and institutional accountability measure.


A. Importance of Documentation in Preschool Settings

In a preschool environment:

  • Teachers work with young, vulnerable children.

  • Trust, safety, and transparency are critical.

  • Regulatory bodies, parents, and management expect proper verification.

Therefore, no teacher enters the classroom without completing documentation and verification.


B. Appointment Letter & Employment Confirmation

1. Appointment Letter Overview

The appointment letter formally confirms:

  • Designation: Class Teacher / Assistant / Support / Floater

  • Nature of employment: Full-time / Part-time / Contract

  • Terms: Joining date, probation period, and reporting authority

  • Compensation: Salary structure and payment cycle

  • Logistics: Working hours, weekly off, and leave eligibility

  • Ethics: Code of conduct acceptance

Teacher Responsibility

  1. Read the appointment letter carefully.

  2. Clarify doubts before signing.

  3. Sign and submit the acceptance copy.


C, D, & E. Verification Requirements

Verification Category

Required Documents

Primary Purpose

Personal Identity

Government-issued Photo ID (Aadhaar / Passport / Voter ID), Address proof, Recent passport-size photos.

Identity confirmation, emergency contact accuracy, and legal compliance.

Educational Qualification

Highest educational certificates, Teacher training/ECCE certificates, Mark sheets.

Ensure academic eligibility and assign appropriate classroom roles.

Experience (If Applicable)

Experience letters, relieving letters, and reference contact details.

Validate prior teaching history and assist in mentoring needs.


F. Background Verification & Safety Declaration

1. Police Verification / Self-Declaration

As teachers work with children, they must provide:

  • Official Police Verification OR

  • A signed Self-Declaration of no criminal record (subject to local regulations).

2. Child Safety Declaration

Teachers must formally declare:

  • Commitment to child safety.

  • Zero tolerance towards abuse, neglect, or inappropriate conduct.

  • Willingness to strictly follow all safeguarding policies.


G. Medical Fitness & Health Declaration

Documents Required:

  • Basic medical fitness declaration.

  • Disclosure of any condition affecting classroom safety (voluntary & confidential).

Purpose: To ensure the physical ability to manage classroom duties, protect the health of children/staff, and ensure emergency preparedness.


H. Emergency Contact & Personal Information Form

Teachers must submit the following for safety and emergency purposes only:

  • Emergency contact details.

  • Blood group (if required).

  • Allergy or medical alerts (optional).

  • Updated address and phone number.


I. Confidentiality & Data Protection Agreement

Teachers must sign a confidentiality agreement with these Key Commitments:

  • No sharing of child information outside the school.

  • No posting of child photos/videos on personal social media.

  • No discussion of internal matters with outsiders.

  • Responsible use of school data and communication tools.


J. Code of Conduct & Professional Ethics Agreement

This agreement sets clear behavioral boundaries regarding:

  • Professional behavior standards and respectful language.

  • Appropriate physical interaction guidelines.

  • Social media and digital conduct rules.

  • Dress code and workplace etiquette.


K. Document Verification Checklist & HR Sign-Off

Stakeholder

Responsibility

HR / Admin

Verify all documents, match originals with copies, maintain secure staff files, and record completion.

Teacher

Ensure timely submission, update changes immediately, and cooperate with the verification process.


L. Clearance for Classroom Entry

CRITICAL REQUIREMENT: A teacher is officially cleared to enter the classroom and interact with children ONLY after:

  1. All documents are verified.

  2. All declarations are signed.

  3. Final HR clearance is granted.

pages.title: Code of conduct, confidentiality & data privacy agreement
pages.content:
üè´ Purpose of This Module

This module establishes the core foundations for professional practice within our institution:

  • Professional behavior standards expected from all teachers
  • Ethical boundaries while working with young children
  • Confidentiality rules to protect children, parents, and the institution

Pro-Tip: In a preschool, conduct and confidentiality are non-negotiable because teachers work with vulnerable children and sensitive family information.


A. Understanding Code of Conduct in a Preschool

What is a Code of Conduct?

The Code of Conduct defines the essential framework for our professional environment:

  • How teachers behave
  • How they communicate
  • How they interact with children, parents, colleagues, and management
  • What constitutes acceptable and unacceptable behavior

Scope of Application

It applies in the following contexts:

  1. Inside classrooms
  2. On school premises
  3. During school events, trips, and celebrations
  4. In digital communication and social media
  5. Outside school, when representing the institution

B. Professional Conduct with Children

Expected Standards Strictly Prohibited
  • Treat every child with respect, patience, and dignity
  • Use positive, calm, and age-appropriate language
  • Maintain a warm but professional relationship
  • Follow approved touch and care guidelines
  • Ensure emotional and physical safety at all times
  • Shouting, threatening, or humiliating a child
  • Physical punishment or force
  • Sarcasm, labeling, or comparison
  • Fear-based discipline
  • Any form of emotional, physical, or verbal abuse

Core Philosophy: Discipline in preschool means guidance, not punishment.


C. Professional Conduct with Parents

Expected Behavior Boundaries
  • Communicate politely, clearly, and respectfully
  • Share information factually, without judgment
  • Maintain confidentiality of other children and families
  • Direct sensitive matters through proper channels
  • No personal arguments or confrontations
  • No sharing internal issues with parents
  • No discussing other children or staff
  • No promises beyond school policy

D. Professional Conduct with Colleagues & Management

Expected Standards

  • Mutual respect and teamwork
  • Constructive communication
  • Following hierarchy and reporting lines
  • Cooperation during events and emergencies

Unacceptable Behavior

  • Gossip or negative talk
  • Undermining colleagues or coordinators
  • Disrespectful language or behavior
  • Creating a hostile or unsafe work environment

E. Dress Code & Personal Presentation

Teachers are role models. Personal presentation should reflect professionalism and safety.

Professional Standards Not Allowed
  • Neat, clean, and professional appearance
  • Comfortable attire suitable for active classrooms
  • Modest and child-appropriate clothing
  • Revealing or inappropriate attire
  • Unsafe accessories (long nails, sharp jewelry)
  • Clothing that restricts movement or safety

F. Digital Conduct & Social Media Policy

Strict Confidentiality Rules

  • Never post photos or videos of children on personal social media
  • Never share child names, faces, or personal details online
  • Use only approved school platforms for communication

Professional Online Behavior

  • Avoid posting content that may harm school reputation
  • No negative comments about school, parents, or colleagues
  • Follow school guidelines for digital communication

G. Confidentiality Policy

What is Confidential Information?

Confidential information includes, but is not limited to:

  • Child personal details
  • Developmental observations and reports
  • Parent information and concerns
  • Internal school documents and policies
  • Staff information

Teacher Responsibilities

  • Keep all information secure
  • Discuss child matters only with authorized staff
  • Never discuss children or families outside school
  • Protect documents, files, and digital data

Important Note: Confidentiality applies during and after employment.


H. Child Safety & Ethical Boundaries

Maintaining safety is our primary objective:

  • Follow child safeguarding policies strictly
  • Maintain professional boundaries at all times
  • Report any concerns or incidents immediately
  • Never ignore or hide safety issues

Failure to follow child safety protocols is considered a serious violation.


I. Reporting Misconduct & Whistleblowing

Teachers are encouraged to:

  • Report unethical behavior or safety concerns
  • Follow internal reporting procedures
  • Speak up without fear of retaliation

Protecting children is everyone‚Äôs responsibility.


J. Consequences of Policy Violation

Violation of the Code of Conduct or Confidentiality may result in:

  1. Verbal or written warning
  2. Suspension pending enquiry
  3. Termination of employment
  4. Legal action (in serious cases)

Warning: Ignorance of rules is not an excuse.


K. Teacher Acknowledgement & Commitment

At the end of this module, teachers must:

  • Read and understand the Code of Conduct
  • Agree to follow confidentiality and ethical guidelines
  • Sign the Code of Conduct & Confidentiality Declaration

This acknowledgement is a mandatory requirement for employment continuation.

pages.title: Role clarity: class teacher vs assistant vs floater vs coordinator
pages.content:
Purpose of the Induction Timeline

The induction timeline ensures that:

  • New teachers are gradually integrated, not overwhelmed

  • Classroom exposure is structured and safe

  • Expectations are clear at every stage

  • Learning, observation, and responsibility are phased logically

This timeline focuses on confidence-building before performance.

üóìÔ∏è PHASE 1: DAY 1 ‚Äì Welcome & Orientation

Objective

To help the teacher feel welcomed, informed, and oriented, without classroom pressure.

Day 1 Focus Areas

1. Formal Welcome & Introduction

  • Welcome by management / academic head

  • Introduction to school vision, values, and culture

  • Overview of induction journey

2. Administrative Completion

  • Verification of appointment documentation

  • Submission of pending forms (if any)

  • HR briefing on attendance, leave, and payroll basics

3. Campus & Facility Orientation

  • Classroom areas

  • Washrooms & hygiene stations

  • Staff room & storage areas

  • Emergency exits & safety points

4. Introduction to Team

  • Meeting coordinator, mentor, and colleagues

  • Understanding reporting structure

  • Assignment of mentor / buddy

5. Policy & Safety Briefing

  • Code of conduct recap

  • Child safety & safeguarding overview

  • Confidentiality & digital conduct reminder

Day 1 Expectations from the Teacher

  • Observe and listen

  • Ask questions freely

  • No classroom responsibility unless assigned

  • Complete induction checklist

Outcome of Day 1

  • Teacher feels welcomed and secure

  • Knows ‚Äúwho is who‚Äù and ‚Äúwhere is what‚Äù

  • Understands basic rules and expectations

üóìÔ∏è PHASE 2: WEEK 1 ‚Äì Observation & Guided Participation

Objective

To help the teacher understand classroom functioning through observation and supported involvement.

Week 1 Focus Areas

1. Classroom Observation

  • Observe mentor teacher‚Äôs classroom

  • Understand daily routines and transitions

  • Watch child behavior management techniques

  • Note teacher-child communication style

2. Curriculum Familiarization

  • Overview of curriculum framework

  • Understanding daily schedule

  • Introduction to lesson plans and activity flow

3. Assisted Classroom Participation

  • Support activities under supervision

  • Help with transitions, snack time, toileting routines

  • Engage with children under guidance

4. Safety & Hygiene Practice

  • Supervision norms

  • Handwashing routines

  • Incident reporting procedure

5. Daily Reflection & Feedback

  • End-of-day check-in with mentor

  • Clarification of doubts

  • Observation notes and learning points

Week 1 Expectations from the Teacher

  • Observe actively, not passively

  • Follow instructions carefully

  • Maintain professional conduct

  • Show willingness to learn and adapt

Outcome of Week 1

  • Teacher understands classroom rhythm

  • Begins connecting theory to practice

  • Builds comfort with children and routines

üóìÔ∏è PHASE 3: MONTH 1 ‚Äì Supported Responsibility & Evaluation

Objective

To gradually transition the teacher into independent classroom responsibility with support.

Month 1 Focus Areas

1. Gradual Role Ownership

  • Take charge of small group activities

  • Lead circle time or activity sessions

  • Manage routines with mentor support

2. Lesson Planning & Execution

  • Prepare lesson plans (guided)

  • Use teaching aids effectively

  • Adapt activities for mixed abilities

3. Classroom Management Practice

  • Apply positive discipline strategies

  • Handle minor behavioral challenges

  • Maintain calm classroom environment

4. Observation & Documentation

  • Record basic child observations

  • Maintain activity and progress notes

  • Learn reporting formats

5. Parent Interaction (Limited & Guided)

  • Observe parent communication

  • Participate in handovers if permitted

  • Learn communication protocols

6. Continuous Feedback & Coaching

  • Weekly review meetings

  • Strengths and improvement areas discussion

  • Goal setting for next phase

Month 1 Expectations from the Teacher

  • Demonstrate responsibility and consistency

  • Accept feedback constructively

  • Follow SOPs independently

  • Show alignment with school culture

Outcome of Month 1

  • Teacher is classroom-ready

  • Understands systems and expectations

  • Builds confidence and professional identity

  • Ready for probation confirmation or next-level responsibility

```
pages.title: Mentor allocation & buddy system
pages.content:
Mentor Allocation & Buddy System üìö

Purpose of This Module

  • Feels supported, not isolated

  • Learns school practices through guided experience

  • Transitions smoothly from theory to classroom practice

  • Receives consistent feedback and emotional support

This system reduces early attrition, anxiety, and classroom errors.

Understanding the Mentor & Buddy System

What is a Mentor?

  • Guide professional development

  • Support classroom skills

  • Provide structured feedback

  • Ensure quality and consistency

What is a Buddy?

  • Helps with day-to-day questions

  • Assists with routines and logistics

  • Provides informal guidance and reassurance

Mentor: Professional guide

Buddy: Daily support partner

Objectives of Mentor Allocation

  • Accelerate learning and confidence

  • Maintain teaching quality standards

  • Ensure child safety and consistency

  • Provide a safe space for questions and mistakes

Criteria for Mentor Selection

  • Minimum experience and proven classroom competence

  • Strong understanding of school culture and SOPs

  • Positive attitude and leadership qualities

  • Communication and coaching skills

  • Professional conduct and reliability

Note: Only approved mentors may guide new teachers.

Mentor Roles & Responsibilities

Professional Guidance

  • Explain classroom routines and expectations

  • Demonstrate best teaching practices

  • Guide lesson planning and activity execution

Observation & Feedback

  • Observe new teacher‚Äôs classroom interactions

  • Provide constructive, timely feedback

  • Identify strengths and improvement areas

Emotional Support

  • Address anxieties and confidence issues

  • Encourage reflective practice

  • Promote positive mindset

Monitoring & Reporting

  • Track induction progress

  • Submit mentor feedback reports

  • Recommend readiness for independent responsibility

Buddy Roles & Responsibilities

Daily Operational Support

  • Help locate materials and resources

  • Clarify daily schedules and routines

  • Assist with administrative processes

Informal Guidance

  • Answer quick questions

  • Share practical tips

  • Help new teacher feel comfortable

Team Integration

  • Introduce colleagues

  • Encourage participation in staff activities

  • Promote positive team culture

New Teacher Responsibilities in the System

  • Actively seek guidance

  • Respect mentor and buddy roles

  • Be open to feedback

  • Maintain professionalism

  • Communicate challenges honestly

Note: Mentorship is a two-way partnership, not a one-way evaluation.

Mentor‚ÄìMentee Interaction Structure

Scheduled Interactions

  • Daily check-ins (first week)

  • Weekly review meetings (first month)

  • Classroom observation sessions

Informal Interactions

  • On-the-spot guidance

  • Post-class reflection

  • Clarification of doubts

Duration of Mentorship

Standard mentorship period: First 30‚Äì60 days

Extended support if required

Formal closure after induction review

Boundaries & Professional Conduct

  • Maintain confidentiality

  • Avoid favoritism

  • Provide guidance, not authority misuse

  • Escalate concerns professionally

Monitoring & Evaluation

Evaluation Criteria

  • Teaching readiness

  • Classroom management skills

  • Alignment with school values

  • Professional behavior

Tools Used

  • Observation checklists

  • Feedback forms

  • Induction progress tracker

Acknowledgement & Documentation

  • Mentor assignment letter

  • Buddy assignment note

  • Signed understanding by new teacher

  • Induction progress records

```

pages.title: Tour checklist: campus, classrooms, storage, staff areas, exits
pages.content:
Purpose of This Module üéì

This campus tour is not just a walk-through. It ensures that every new teacher:

  • Knows where everything is
  • Understands safe movement and supervision zones
  • Is aware of emergency procedures
  • Can respond confidently during daily routines and emergencies

A teacher who knows the campus well is a safer and more confident caregiver.

A. Campus Orientation ‚Äì Key Areas

1. Entry & Exit Points

  • Main entrance and security desk
  • Child drop-off and pick-up points
  • Authorized entry/exit procedures
  • Visitor management system

Teacher Responsibility

  • Monitor children during arrival/departure
  • Follow handover protocols
  • Ensure children leave only with authorized persons

2. Reception & Administrative Area

  • Front desk communication flow
  • Emergency contact handling
  • Incident reporting access
  • Parent interaction protocol

3. Staff Areas

  • Staff room and lockers
  • Pantry and washroom facilities
  • Staff notice boards
  • Attendance register or biometric system

B. Classroom Orientation

4. Assigned Classroom(s)

  • Classroom layout and learning zones
  • Entry and exit points
  • Storage cupboards and labeling system
  • Display boards and usage guidelines

Key Focus

  • Visibility of children at all times
  • Safe furniture placement
  • Clear walking paths

5. Learning Corners & Activity Areas

  • Reading corner
  • Art and craft area
  • Block/construction zone
  • Sensory or calm-down corner

Safety Focus

  • Age-appropriate materials
  • Safe storage of small or sharp items
  • Clean-up routines

6. Toilets & Hygiene Stations

  • Child toilet locations
  • Handwashing stations
  • Diaper changing or assistance areas (if applicable)
  • Hygiene supply storage

Teacher Responsibility

  • Supervise with dignity and privacy
  • Follow hygiene SOPs
  • Report maintenance issues immediately

C. Common Areas

7. Indoor Play Areas

  • Activity rooms / multipurpose halls
  • Equipment usage rules
  • Supervision points

8. Outdoor Play Area

  • Entry and exit control
  • Play equipment safety checks
  • Shade and hydration points
  • Safe boundaries

Teacher Responsibility

  • Maintain child count
  • Prevent unsafe play
  • Follow outdoor supervision ratios

9. Dining / Snack Areas

  • Seating arrangement
  • Food handling and allergy protocols
  • Clean-up routines

D. Safety & Emergency Orientation

10. Emergency Exits & Evacuation Routes

  • Fire exits from classrooms and common areas
  • Evacuation maps
  • Assembly points

Teachers must be able to:

  • Lead children calmly
  • Count children before and after evacuation

11. Fire Safety Equipment

  • Fire extinguishers (locations & types)
  • Fire alarm system
  • Emergency switches

12. First Aid & Medical Room

  • First aid kit locations
  • Medical room or isolation area
  • Sick child handling protocol

13. CCTV & Security Systems

  • CCTV coverage areas
  • Blind spots (if any)
  • Monitoring protocol

E. Child Safety & Supervision Zones

14. High-Risk Zones Awareness

  • Staircases
  • Washrooms
  • Outdoor play area
  • Entry/exit points

Teacher Responsibility

  • Extra supervision
  • Never leave children unattended

F. Incident & Emergency Reporting Points

15. Incident Reporting

  • Accident report forms
  • Whom to inform immediately
  • Documentation process

G. End-of-Tour Confirmation

16. Teacher Acknowledgement

At the end of the tour, teachers must:

  • Confirm familiarity with campus layout
  • Acknowledge understanding of safety points
  • Ask clarifying questions

(Optional)

  • Signed tour checklist
  • Emergency readiness confirmation
